The experiment `bow_20260427_165835_run_03` using a Bag of Words (BoW) architecture achieved a reasonable performance with an F1 score of 0.7625 and accuracy of 0.7975, indicating that the model effectively captured the underlying patterns in the data for classification tasks related to disaster tweets. The use of TF-IDF vectorization up to n-grams (ngram_max=2) and a moderate number of features (max_features=11000) contributed positively to the model's performance. However, there is room for improvement as the F1 score could be higher, suggesting that either more sophisticated feature extraction techniques or a different model architecture might yield better results. For the next run, consider experimenting with additional n-grams, exploring other vectorization methods like word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec, GloVe), or tuning hyperparameters such as the regularization strength (`logreg_c`) to optimize performance further.